### Part 1: Introduction

The quadratic formula is a fundamental concept in algebra used to solve quadratic equations of the form ax^2 + bx + c = 0. In this program, we will utilize the quadratic formula to calculate the roots of the equation: x = (-b ± sqrt(b^2 - 4ac)) / (2a).

### Part 2: Quadratic Formula Implementation

To implement the quadratic formula in C, we will use the following steps:

*   Calculate the discriminant (b^2 - 4ac)
*   Check if the discriminant is positive, negative, or zero
*   Use the quadratic formula to calculate the roots of the equation

### Part 3: C Program Implementation

Here is a simple C program that implements the quadratic formula:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <math.h>

// Function to calculate the roots of a quadratic equation
void calculate_roots(double a, double b, double c) {
    // Calculate the discriminant
    double discriminant = pow(b, 2) - 4 * a * c;

    // Check if the discriminant is positive, negative, or zero
    if (discriminant > 0) {
        // Two distinct real roots
        double root1 = (-b + sqrt(discriminant)) / (2 * a);
        double root2 = (-b - sqrt(discriminant)) / (2 * a);
        printf("The roots of the equation are: %.2f and %.2f\n", root1, root2);
    } else if (discriminant == 0) {
        // One real root
        double root = -b / (2 * a);
        printf("The root of the equation is: %.2f\n", root);
    } else {
        // No real roots
        printf("The equation has no real roots.\n");
    }
}

int main() {
    // Coefficients of the quadratic equation
    double a = 1;
    double b = -5;
    double c = 6;

    // Calculate and display the roots
    calculate_roots(a, b, c);

    return 0;
}
```

This program takes the coefficients a, b, and c as input and calculates the roots of the quadratic equation using the quadratic formula. The roots are then displayed on the console.
